<!-- Begin Title -->
<h1>Laplace Transform</h1>
<!-- End Title -->
<hr class=3D"margin-t-1-8 margin-b-3-4">
<!-- Begin Total Content -->
<div class=3D"attachments text-align-r">
<a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/notebooks/IntegralTransforms/Lapla=
ceTransform.nb" download=3D"LaplaceTransform.nb"><img src=3D"https://mathwo=
rld.wolfram.com/images/entries/download-notebook-icon.png" width=3D"26" hei=
ght=3D"27" alt=3D"DOWNLOAD Mathematica Notebook"><span>Download
 <span class=3D"display-i display-n__600">Wolfram&nbsp;</span>Notebook</spa=
n></a>
</div>
<!-- Begin Content -->
<div class=3D"entry-content">
<p>
The Laplace transform is an <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Integr=
alTransform.html">integral transform</a> perhaps second only to the <a href=
=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/FourierTransform.html">Fourier transform<=
/a>
 in its utility in solving physical problems. The Laplace transform is part=
icularly
 useful in solving linear <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Ordinary=
DifferentialEquation.html">ordinary differential
 equations</a> such as those arising in the analysis of electronic circuits=
.
</p>
<p>
The (unilateral) Laplace transform <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.co=
m/images/equations/LaplaceTransform/Inline1.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" st=
yle=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"13" height=3D"=
21" alt=3D"L"> (not to be confused with the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wo=
lfram.com/LieDerivative.html">Lie
 derivative</a>, also commonly denoted <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfra=
m.com/images/equations/LaplaceTransform/Inline2.svg" class=3D"inlineformula=
" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"13" height=
=3D"21" alt=3D"L">) is defined by
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/LaplaceTransform/NumberedEquation1.svg" class=3D"numberedequa=
tion" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"206" h=
eight=3D"39" alt=3D" L_t[f(t)](s)=3Dint_0^inftyf(t)e^(-st)dt, "></td><td al=
ign=3D"right" width=3D"3">
<div id=3D"eqn1" class=3D"eqnum">
(1)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
where <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/LaplaceTra=
nsform/Inline3.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-wi=
dth:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"31" height=3D"21" alt=3D"f(t)">
 is defined for <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/=
LaplaceTransform/Inline4.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:1=
00%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"33" height=3D"21" alt=3D"t&gt;=3D=
0">
 (Abramowitz and Stegun 1972). The unilateral Laplace transform is almost a=
lways what
 is meant by "the" Laplace transform, although a <a href=3D"https://mathwor=
ld.wolfram.com/BilateralLaplaceTransform.html">bilateral
 Laplace transform</a> is sometimes also defined as
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/LaplaceTransform/NumberedEquation2.svg" class=3D"numberedequa=
tion" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"215" h=
eight=3D"39" alt=3D" L_t^((2))[f(t)](s)=3Dint_(-infty)^inftyf(t)e^(-st)dt "=
></td><td align=3D"right" width=3D"3">
<div id=3D"eqn2" class=3D"eqnum">
(2)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
(Oppenheim <i>et al. </i>1997). The unilateral Laplace transform <img src=
=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/LaplaceTransform/Inline5=
.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" bord=
er=3D"0" width=3D"86" height=3D"21" alt=3D"L_t[f(t)](s)"> is implemented in=
 the <a href=3D"http://www.wolfram.com/language/">Wolfram
 Language</a> as <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wolfram.com/language/ref/L=
aplaceTransform.html">LaplaceTransform</a></tt>[<i>f[t]</i>,
 <i>t</i>, <i>s</i>] and the inverse Laplace transform as <tt><a href=3D"ht=
tp://reference.wolfram.com/language/ref/InverseRadonTransform.html">Inverse=
RadonTransform</a></tt>.
</p>
<p>
The inverse Laplace transform is known as the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.=
wolfram.com/BromwichIntegral.html">Bromwich integral</a>, sometimes known a=
s the Fourier-Mellin integral (see also the related
 Duhamel's convolution principle).
</p>
<p>
A table of several important one-sided Laplace transforms is given below.
</p>
